<!--
VOICING PLAN:
- Non-diatonic substitutions for lever harp (Eb key):
  - ^F (F# in melody) → treat as Fm(ii) passing — harp plays F natural diatonic
  - C#°7 → D°7 (vii°7 in Eb: D-F-Ab-C) — close to vii°7 of the key
  - G# = Ab = IV (Ab major) — diatonic!
  - F#°7 → D°(vii°) — substitute diminished
  - EbΔ7 → IΔ7 (Eb major 7th: Eb-G-Bb-D) — fully diatonic in Eb
  - Dø7 → D°7 = vii°7 — used as leading-tone tension
  - G(nat) → Gm(iii) — use minor mediant
  - Gm7 → IIIm7 (Gm7: G-Bb-D-F) — all diatonic notes!
  - C(nat) → Cm(vi) — use minor sixth
  - =A (A natural) → appears only as a chromatic melody note; harp avoids it

- IV (Ab): Ab-Eb-Ab quartal voicing ("44") used consistently — two perfect 4ths
- vii°7 (D°7): D-Ab-C = open diminished cluster with Ab (4th in LH)
- IΔ7 at m3: Eb-Bb-D-G spread — the D (major 7th) gives warmth without being jarring
- vi7 (Cm7): C-G-Eb-Bb = all diatonic; spread 7th chord creates the most complex texture
- Final I: 4-note LH (Eb-Bb-Eb-G) + 4-note RH (Eb-G-Bb-Eb) — maximum density at close

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- Bass descent mm.1-4: Eb2→F2→Eb2→D2→Ab2→... constant stepwise movement
- Inner voice m6: G2→G2→C2→Eb2 — bass holds then descends third to tonic
- m7 ascending line: iii→vi→I→vi7 — G→C→Eb→C, inner voice D→Eb→Eb→Eb common tone
- Final V→IV→I: Bb2→Ab2→Eb2 descending bass — classic 5-4-1 Baroque cadence pattern

TEXTURE ARC:
- Pickup + m1: 3-note LH, 3-note RH — fresh opening
- mm. 2-3: Add 3rd to LH (IΔ7 at m3 is the first "333" voicing); RH gets 3 notes at I
- mm. 4-5: vii°7 contrast with open D-Ab texture; then I rebuilds to 4-note (m5 beat3)
- mm. 6-7: iii and vi colors; vi7 at m7 beat4 is the emotional peak (RH reaches G5)
- m8 final: V chord with D4 at top of LH (11th span!) → IV rich → I convergence at Eb
-->
